M a n B i r d â„¢ 2023-12-18 3:41 PM
for what i know from actual studios and all mastering is often controlling the dynamics so with compression and limiting to have it be at a consistent volume both throuhgout the track as well as compared to other music, and maybe indeed some eq adjustments to have a better representation of all frequencies so its not that one stands out too much and takes up all the headroom for said compression and limiting
3:47 PM
in terms of doing everything yourself tho, as long as you have a good reference in the same (ish) style as your track and the frequency distribution is in the same ballpark with volume not drastically different, then youre good. theres help for that like tonal balance control where you can visualize your frequenices compared to a target style or genre, and in terms of volume, as long as its not clipping and overly compressed and to a point where you can hear every part nicely without having to adjust volume halfway thru, youre in a good place
